                                <support><p><ref target="https://canmore.org.uk/site/18978/chapel-of-garioch-the-maiden-stone">Canmore</ref> <idno type="Canmore">18978</idno></p>
                                    <material>Pinkish granite</material> 
                                    <objectType>Class II cross-slab</objectType>                                     
                                    <dimensions unit="m">                                         
                                            <height>3.01</height>
                                            <width max="0.91" min="0.81">0.91-0.81</width>
                                            <depth max="0.30" min="0.15">0.30-0.15</depth>
                                     </dimensions>         
                                </support>
                                <condition>The slab <q>is missing a triangular shaped fragment from one of its sides and has a triangular cutaway at its base</q> (Barnes 2017, 2).</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout><q>The front face exhibits a <rs type="decoration">ring-headed Christian cross</rs>, carved all in relief, with a <rs type="decoration">male figure</rs> and <rs type="decoration">two fish monsters</rs> above. There are numerous panels decorated with <rs type="decoration">interlace</rs>, <rs type="decoration">knotwork</rs> and <rs type="decoration">key-pattern</rs> below this, including a <rs type="decoration">circular design</rs> with spiral work at its centre. The back face is split into four panels. These exhibit three <rs type="decoration">Pictish symbol designs</rs> below a <rs type="decoration">centaur</rs> and <rs type="decoration">three other beasts</rs></q> (Barnes 2017, 2). The ogham inscription is located at the base of the back face. <q>The sides are also both carved. The north facing side is carved with <rs type="decoration">Stafford knots</rs>, and the south facing side with <rs type="decoration">interlace</rs></q> (Allen 1903, 191; Barnes 2017, 4).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
